<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation To Cover 58 Percent of Territory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation To Cover 58 Percent of Territory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1205151294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1205151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Edhem Bicakcic, member of the Bosniak </F>
delegation at the Vienna talks, by Amir Hodzic in Vienna; date 
not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Hodzic] Mr. Bicakcic, how much territory will the 
federation cover -- its borders have been set -- and, 
percentage-wise, how many people will it include? 
  [Bicakcic] This issue -- establishing the external borders 
of the federation -- was one of the easier issues, and the 
Bosniak and Croatian delegations relatively quickly reached an 
agreement on it. The territory of the federation covers 58 
percent of the territory of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
including the 3 percent of the Sarajevo district territory. 
  On this territory the Bosniaks and the Croats are in the 
majority, which means that the Bosnia-Herzegovina Assembly's 
decision that territories with majority Bosniak and Croatian 
populations should be included in the federation, has been 
followed to the letter. Apart from the 58 percent of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina territory, the Croatian and the Bosniak 
delegations also expressed an interest in places that would 
remain under the Serbian aggressor's occupation where Bosniaks 
and Croats were in the majority. These are larger cities such 
as Bosanski Petrovac, Bosanska Gradiska, Bosanska Dubica, 
Bijeljina, Janja, and [word indistinct], which cannot be covered 
by the federation territory, but -- in future negotiations, when 
they take place -- we will try to obtain from the Serbian 
aggressor the protection of human rights for the population in 
these areas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

