<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Condemns Muslim Attacks on Brcko </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Condemns Muslim Attacks on Brcko </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205135394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1303 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, May 12 (TANJUG) -- The Russian Foreign 
Ministry on Thursday [12 May] condemned Muslim attacks on Brcko. 
Moscow believes that such attacks lead to further escalation of 
conflicts and that they are especially dangerous prior to the 
forthcoming ministerial conference in Geneva. The chief 
diplomats of the United States, Russia and the European Union 
and officials of the United Nations will meet in Geneva on 
Friday to try to definitively determine the framework for a 
political settlement of the crisis in the former Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The situation around the Serb town of Brcko in the north of 
Bosnia is currently at the focus of attention of political 
organs and the media in Moscow. Radio and television stations 
broadcast the news that the U.N. Security Council had condemned 
the Muslim attack on Brcko in which four civilians were killed 
and 13 wounded. It is believed here that the current situation 
in Bosnia, especially around Brcko, does not inspire a great 
deal of hope for an early settlement of the conflict. 
  Official sources here say that on both sides -- Serb and 
Muslim -- there are forces inclined to military confrontation 
who believe that a political settlement is impossible. Moscow 
has announced that its position in Geneva will be `very 
resolute' but it is not clear whether it will make any new 
proposals. Russia insists on an agreement that the warring 
sides resume talks as soon as possible. If this is not 
achieved, the war could continue indefinitely and the 
consequences could be disastrous, official sources in Moscow 
maintain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

