<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Infighting Continues in Western Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim Infighting Continues in Western Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305012894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2303 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1305012894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 12 (TANJUG) -- Radio Sarajevo, loyal 
to the Bosnian Moslem regime of hardliner Alija Izetbegovic, on 
Thursday again reported fighting between rival Moslem factions 
in western Bosnia-Herzegovina. That part of the war-wracked 
former Yugoslav republic has since last autumn been the scene of 
fierce clashes between troops loyal to [word indistinct] leader 
Izetbegovic and supporters of his moderate rival and local 
leader Fikret Abdic. Abdic's supporters proclaimed their own 
autonomous province of western Bosnia in late September 1993, 
and have since signed friendship and cooperation treaties with 
the other two Bosnian nations -- Serbs and Croats. 
  Radio Sarajevo said that provincial forces on Thursday kept 
up a sustained attack, the brunt of which was directed at the 
village of Todorovo where `nearly all facilities have been 
demolished, including mosques and schools, and there was a 
considerable number of dead and wounded.' The source said that 
the Moslem army's 5th Corps, loyal to Izetbegovic, had managed 
to regain some strategically important positions captured by 
Abdic's troops the day before. The reports could not be 
independently confirmed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

