<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croats To Accept New Croatian Currency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Croats To Accept New Croatian Currency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205211894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2051 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, May 12 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Croat Premier 
Jadranko Prlic said on Thursday that neighbouring Croatia's new 
currency, the kuna, would be used also in the Bosnian Croat 
state of Herzeg-Bosna, Mostar-based Herzeg-Bosna Radio said. 
Croatia will officially circulate the new currency on 
Independence Day, May 30. 
  The currency has the same name -- the kuna -- as that used 
in 
the Nazi-puppet Independent State of Croatia during World War 
Two. 
  Immediately after Croatia's secession from the former 
Yugoslav Federation nearly three years ago, Bosnian Croats 
embraced the breakaway state's then currency -- the Croatian 
dinar -- thus making clear to one and all their ultimate 
objective -- secession from Bosnia-Herzegovina and union with 
Croatia. The Croatian news agency HINA has quoted Prlic as 
admitting that there are forces in Herzeg-Bosna which oppose the 
implementation of the Washington agreement on a Croat-Moslem 
federation in Bosnia- Herzegovina. There are political forces 
among the Croats which oppose the agreement, and there are also 
those who have lost members of immediate family in the fighting 
against the Moslems and do not want a union, Prlic explained. 
  Five-day U.S.-sponsored Croatian-Moslem talks at the U.S. 
embassy in Vienna ended on Wednesday in an agreement on a 
cantonal division of the future federation and the appointment 
of the two nations' officials to top state positions by rote. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

