<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman, Izetbegovic Discuss Vienna Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman, Izetbegovic Discuss Vienna Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205135994 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Franjo Tudjman spoke on the 
telephone to his Bosnian counterpart Alija Izetbegovic today, 
and expressed satisfaction with an agreement reached by the 
Croatian and Bosnian delegations in Vienna on Wednesday evening, 
the presidential office said in a statement today. The two 
presidents agree that the implementation of the Washington 
agreement on establishing a Muslim-Croatian federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina should continue. They also talked about 
solving technical issues to enable President Tudjman to visit 
Sarajevo as soon as possible, and about their joint stand on the 
contact group and the upcoming meeting of foreign ministers in 
Geneva. Tudjman asked Izetbegovic to use his authority to step 
up the process of finding the missing Croats from Bugojno. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55355 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu093_i_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman, Izetbegovic Address Liaison Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman, Izetbegovic Address Liaison Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1205191794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1205191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As we have announced, Presidents Izetbegovic and 
Tudjman today agreed to send an identical letter to the 
ministers of a liaison group in Geneva that will venture on a 
quest tomorrow to restore peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. In the 
two presidents' letter, the following is stated, among other 
things: 
  The delegations of the Bosniaks and the Croats in Vienna 
yesterday reached a concrete and detailed agreement on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's internal setup on the basis of the 
Washington agreement. This agreement offers a chance for an 
overall political solution for Bosnia-Herzegovina on a just 
basis. The Bosniaks and Croats do not harbor any aspirations 
for foreign property and territories, or the rights of others. 
We ask your help in the negotiations with the Serbian side. In 
our opinion, we must make it plain to both the Serbian side and 
the international public, that you are opposed to: 
  -- aggression and ethnic cleansing being rewarded, 
  -- that the conclusions of the London conference are your 
conclusions, too, and, 
  -- that you will neutralize the Serbian military machinery 
in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia by political and other means if 
the Serbs reject a peaceful and reasonable solution. 
  If we are to accomplish peace we need a firm stance. The 
decisions that you will make tomorrow are very important and 
will determine the course of international events, especially in 
the regions where the Communist regime has collapsed. So reads 
the identically-worded letters that Presidents Izetbegovic and 
Tudjman sent to the liaison group ministers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

