<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Approves `Partnership' Documents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Approves `Partnership' Documents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105165094 Prague CTK in English 1505 GMT 11 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1105165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 11 (CTK) -- The Czech Government has 
approved the presentation documents for the Partnership for 
Peace project which the Foreign Ministry is to submit to NATO, 
Defense Minister Antonin Baudys said at a press conference after 
the government session today. 
  The documents are only in draft form and will probably be 
reworked on consultation with NATO, he said. 
  The documents represent an intensification of the 
preparations for Czech membership in the security structures. 
They include consultation in the event of a threat to the 
security of the Czech Republic on the basis of 16+1, i.e. the 
sixteen NATO members plus in such a case the Czech Republic, he 
said. In addition they embrace further political consultation, 
the support of United Nations (U.N.) forces and work on the 
compatibility of the Czech Army with the armies of the alliance. 
  The Czech Republic is to offer its training bases for U.N. 
troop exercises, participate in the organization of study visits 
and continue to cooperate in the military actions of U.N. 
peace-keeping forces. 

</TEXT>

