<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec, Peterle Sign Cooperation Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zieleniec, Peterle Sign Cooperation Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305080094 Prague CTK in English 1644 GMT 12 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1305080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague May 12 (CTK) -- During their meeting today, 
Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec and his Slovenian 
counterpart Lojze Peterle signed a cooperation agreement 
covering education, culture and science, they told journalists. 
  They also talked about the Stability Pact to be signed at 
the 
coming meeting of European foreign ministers in Paris and looked 
at questions of bilateral trade, they said. 
  Trade between the two countries, which have signed a free 
trade zone agreement, has been growing rapidly, with Czech 
exports to Slovenia in the first eight months of last year 
valued at $78 million and Slovenian exports to the Czech 
Republic over the same period amounting to $33 million. 
  Peterle, who started his official two-day visit to the Czech 
Republic today, also met President Vaclav Havel and Parliament 
Chairman Milan Uhde. He will be visiting a Prague Castle 
exhibition about Josip Plecnik, Slovenian architect who worked 
in Czechoslovakia between the two world wars and designed 
alterations to the Castle and its gardens. 
  The ministers agreed on furthering cultural links. The Czech 
Republic is to organise a Czech cultural festival in Ljubljana. 

</TEXT>

