<H3> <TI>   Peterle Sees `No Open Problem' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peterle Sees `No Open Problem' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1305080494 Prague CTK in English 1849 GMT 12 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1305080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague May 12 (CTK) -- The Czech-Slovenian free 
zone agreement will be ratified by parliament as soon as 
possible, Parliament Chairman Milan Uhde said today at his 
meeting with Slovenian Foreign Minister Lojze Peterle. 
  The agreement was signed in Ljubljana on December 4, 1993. 
  Peterle and Uhde pointed to the dynamically-growing 
relations 
between the two countries. 
  Peterle said at the meeting that no open problems existed 
between the two countries and described the Czech Republic as a 
friendly country with strategic importance to Slovenia, for 
which the Czech Republic is the most important partner. 
  He said that Slovenia and the Czech Republic shared views on 
entering the European Union as sovereign countries wanting to 
share in the making of Europe. 
  Uhde criticised attempts at dividing Europe into spheres of 
interest. Peterle said that the idea "leads to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina," adding that if particular pressures had not 
been at play there, the country's problems would have been 
solved a long time ago. 
  "We want a Europe and not a package of interest spheres," 
Peterle added. 

</TEXT>

