<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDP Briefs CSCE Group on School Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PDP Briefs CSCE Group on School Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105163594 Tirana ATA in English 1018 GMT 11 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1105163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, May 11 (ATA) -- The vice president of the 
Party for Democratic Prosperity [PDP], Mendu Thaci, recently met 
in Tetova with CSCE representatives and informed them of the 
difficulties his party is facing, sources from Skopje reported 
yesterday. 
  Mr. Thaci informed the CSCE representatives of the grave 
situation of the Albanian schools in The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia [FYROM]. "In the 1981 there were 38 
Albanian middle schools while now they have been reduced in 5. 
Only 2.8 percent of the Skopje University are Albanians while 
Albanians make up only 2.4 percent of the police workers. Among 
250,000 titles of books at the Skopje Popular Library only 150 
are in Albanian language," Mr. Thaci informed the CSCE 
representatives. 
  "Even Albanians make up one third of the total population, 
they are considered in the Constitution as an insignificant 
minority," Mr. Thaci said adding that "though they were under 
discriminating laws they approved the statement for the 
independence of Macedonia and recognized both its existence and 
that of the Macedonian people." 

</TEXT>

