<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs `Unconditionally' Agree to Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs `Unconditionally' Agree to Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1405174894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1710 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1405174894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 14 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb 
presidential spokesman Jovan Zametica said on Saturday [14 May] 
that the "Serb side accepts, unconditionally, the proposal for a 
general cessation of hostilities contained in the joint 
declaration" issued by seven states' foreign ministers in Geneva 
on Friday. "This, after all, has been or own proposal for a 
long time. But we are in favour of a permanent cessation of 
hostilities, not merely for four months," stressed Zametica in a 
statement faxed to TANJUG's Belgrade office from the cabinet of 
Bosnian Serb President Radovan Karadzic. "The time limit on the 
cessation of hostilities envisaged in the joint declaration is 
harmful to the peace process," maintains Zametica. 
  The foreign ministers of Russia, the United States, Great 
Britain, France and the European Union's "troika" (Belgium, 
Greece, Germany) on Friday invited Bosnia's warring Moslems, 
Serbs and Croats to agree to a four-month ceasefire, "with 
provision for extenscon," in which to negotiate a solution to 
their disputes. 
  The ministers, who coordinated a common strategy in the 
efforts to end the Bosnian conflict, invited the warring nations 
to make a serious effort, without prior conditions, for reaching 
a political settlement of the crisis. The ministers approved 
the European Union's formula which envisages for dividing 
war-shattered Bosnia-Herzegovina in a manner which would give 
the Moslems and Croats 51 percent of the original territory in 
which to form their federation, and the Serbs the remaining 49 
percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55411 </DOCNO>
