<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inter-Muslim Fighting Reported in Northwest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inter-Muslim Fighting Reported in Northwest </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1405175294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1724 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1405175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Petrovac, May 14 (TANJUG) -- Fierce inter-Moslem 
fighting continued on Saturday for the sixth consecutive day in 
the Cazin Krajina, in the northwest of the former Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, local Moslem media reported. 
Reports on the situation on the front are, however, 
contradictory. According to Radio Velkaton based in Velika 
Kladusa, the center of the Moslem Autonomous Province of West 
Bosnia (APZB), APZB supporters have in the past 24 hours 
captured a very important height near Cazin and have inflicted 
huge casualties and losses in equipment on the forces loyal to 
the Moslem authorities in Sarajevo. APZB forces have suffered, 
as the radio said, minimum losses. 
  Radio Velkaton said that troops of the army loyal to the 
Bosnian Moslem hardline leader, Alija Izetbegovic, are still 
deserting in large numbers and joining the ranks of the 
supporters of his moderate rival, Fikret Abdic. According to 
Radio Cazin, a town under control of Izetbegovic's forces, the 
forces loyal to Izetbegovic have managed to recapture an 
important portion of the territories near Cazin in the past 24 
hours. 
  Inter-Moslem fighting has been underway in the Cazin Krajina 
since last October, when Abdic proclaimed the APZB opposing 
Izetbegovic's belligerent policy. He also immediatelly 
concluded peace agreements with Bosnian Serbs and Croats. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

