<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Deliveries to Slovenia Suspended </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Oil Deliveries to Slovenia Suspended </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305140094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1222 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1305140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, May 13 (TANJUG) -- Croatia's Adriatic oil 
company has impounded 15,000 tons of oil the Slovenian firm 
Petrol of Ljubljana has bought in Russia until the Slovenian oil 
refinery in Lendava settles its outstanding debt of 1.4 million 
Deutsche marks with the Adriatic oil. Croatia has also 
suspended all light oil deliveries to Slovenia's only refinery 
in Lendava until it has paid back the 8.5 million dollars it 
owes to Naftaplin in Zagreb for light oil deliveries made so 
far. The Slovenia-Croatia silent oil war threatens to seriously 
undermine the already tense relations between the two 
neighbouring countries which seceded from the former Yugoslav 
federation in 1991. Relations between the two sides are 
especially burdened by the unresolved border and property 
issues, over 600 million dollars in unsettled claims of private 
depositors with the Ljubljanska Banka and deterioration in 
economic relations. 

</TEXT>

