<H3> <TI>   Draft Dodgers To Face `Use of Force' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Draft Dodgers To Face `Use of Force' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305173194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1445 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1305173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 13 May (TANJUG) -- The relevant 
authorities shall warn conscripts who fail to respond to a 
general mobilization call up about the possibility of the use of 
force, although the period of time necessary for reporting 
cannot be shorter than 12 hours. This is the essence of the new 
Federal Government regulation on the mobilization of citizens, 
whose Article 35, as announced by the Federal Defense Ministry's 
information service, says: 
  "If citizens-conscripts do not respond to a general 
mobilization call up in numbers prescribed by individual 
mobilization plans, relevant district bodies, that is 
military-territorial bodies, will order the mobilization service 
to directly and personally inform the conscript who failed to 
report and warn him about the possibility of the use of force if 
he does not report in a period of time not shorter than 12 
hours." 
  One of the innovations in this regulation is that the 
mobilization of combat units and institutions will be carried 
out in due time and gradually and that, unlike what was 
prescribed by regulations until now, only certain institutions 
or parts of institutions, as well as an optimal number of 
conscripts needed for the consolidation of the country's defense 
system, will be liable to mobilization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

