<H3> <TI>   General Staff Denies Troops Fighting in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General Staff Denies Troops Fighting in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305144894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1324 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1305144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 13 May (TANJUG) -- The General Staff of 
the Army of Yugoslavia issued a statement today reiterating that 
"there are no members of the Army of Yugoslavia outside of the 
borders of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and therefore not 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina either." 
  The statement reads: 
  "Some false reports of a rather primitive type on the 
participation of units of the Army of Yugoslavia in the war in 
the former Yugoslavia have again appeared in some media. These 
articles are trying to present the Army of Yugoslavia in the 
same light as the units of the regular Croatian Army, whose 
participation in combat activities in the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina is indisputable. 
  The General Staff of the Army of Yugoslavia has on several 
occasions, in connection with this, informed Yugoslav and world 
public that no members of its Army are outside the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia. This fact has been acknowledged several 
times in statements by UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] military 
officials and political functionaries of the countries whose 
forces are serving within UNPROFOR. 
  Reiterating accusations against the Army of Yugoslavia 
despite the facts in an atmosphere of a serious aggravation of 
the conflict raises the question of the motives and objectives 
of such risky schemes. 
  To assign blame for the war to an army that is not taking 
part in it, and to absolve of responsibility the forces that 
cause and aggravate it, cannot be seen in any other sense than 
propaganda support for the escalation of the war. 
  The General Staff of the Army of Yugoslavia again reiterates 
its commitment to the peaceful resolution of the conflict, while 
following with greatest attention the developments that could 
affect the security of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and 
the survival of the Serb people wherever they live. 
  There are no members of the Yugoslav Army anywhere outside 
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and therefore not in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina either," the statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

