<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Calls For Talks To End Bosnian War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Calls For Talks To End Bosnian War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605112994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1032 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 16 May (TANJUG) -- Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic today received Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian 
president's special envoy, who arrived in Belgrade late last 
night. Churkin informed Milosevic about the results of the 
recent ministerial talks in Geneva on the resolution of the 
conflict in the Balkans. 
  After the talks with Milosevic, which lasted for 90 minutes, 
Churkin said in a statement to reporters that he has come to 
Belgrade after a very important ministerial meeting in Geneva, 
"where we set the framework for what is -- I hope -- the 
completion of the process to resolve the conflict in Bosnia." 
  Churkin said that the participants of the Geneva talks are 
in 
contact "with all sides" to explain the possible effects and the 
essence of the decisions taken in Geneva. In that context he 
recalled that he has already held talks with Bosnian Muslim 
Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic, but did not specify what 
response he received from him. He did, however, stress that 
"President Milosevic and Belgrade fully support the Geneva 
decisions on the ending of hostilities in Bosnia." 
  What after Geneva? The Russian envoy said that he will 
recommend to Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy for Yugoslavia, that talks be arranged between the parties 
to the Bosnian conflict as soon as possible to try to achieve at 
least one target of the Geneva agreement-- an end to hostilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55439 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu094_y_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Begins Talks With Russian Patriarch </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Begins Talks With Russian Patriarch </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605113694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1046 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

