<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose Dissatisfied With Movement in Mostar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rose Dissatisfied With Movement in Mostar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605182994 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1700 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] After a tour of Mostar today, General Michael 
Rose, the commander of the peacekeeping forces for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, said he was dissatisfied with what had been 
done to enable the civilians to cross freely from one part of 
town to the other. It is easier for civilians to cross from one 
part of Sarajevo to the other than from the eastern to the 
western part of Mostar and vice versa, Rose said, adding that 
the freedom to cross from one part of Mostar to the other was 
like the freedom to cross from East to West Berlin during the 
Cold War. In his talks with representatives of civilian and 
military authorities of the western part of Mostar, he said that 
much more had been done in central Bosnia to implement the 
Washington agreement, and in particular to provide free movement 
of civilians. 
  Representatives of authorities of western Mostar said it was 
better to normalize life in Mostar slowly but surely, than hurry 
and make quite possible mistakes, which could reverse the peace 
process back to the starting point. What has been done so far 
to completely end the fighting is a lot for Mostar, 
representatives of Croatian authorities said, adding that the 
latest Croat-Bosniak political agreements would certainly 
stimulate the normalization of life in Mostar. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55490 </DOCNO>
