<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koljevic: EU Policy `More Realistic' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Koljevic: EU Policy `More Realistic' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1605150894 Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI in Serbo-Croatian 16 
May 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU1605150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by M. L.: "The Most Important Thing -- End of the </F>
War"] 
  [Text] The European plan for an approach to solving the 
crisis in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina is better and more 
realistic than the United States' plan and it is good that it 
prevailed at the meeting in Geneva. Of course, there are bound 
to be problems, but they can be solved. The most important 
thing is that this plan envisages the cessation of hostilities, 
which means the continuation of the peace talks, Nikola 
Koljevic, vice president of the Serbian republic, told Radio 
Kragujevac yesterday. Commenting on the declaration of the 
ministerial council in Geneva, and the proposed division of 
territory -- 49 percent for the Serbs, 51 percent for the 
Muslims and Croats -- he said that the Serbian side was ready to 
correct the borders if functional entities are created, that is, 
if the quality and quantity of territory are treated equally. 

</TEXT>

