<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Defense Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Defense Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605204794 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Warsaw today, Poland's and Sweden's defense 
ministers, Piotr Kolodziejczyk and Anders Bjorck, signed an 
intergovernment agreement on defense issues. It covers the 
exchange of information, military training, and cooperation 
between arms-manufacturing companies. Following the good 
experience of collaboration between the Mesko Engineering Works 
and the Swedish Bofors, both sides are hoping that Swedish 
participation in modernizing our Iryda and Skorpion aircraft, as 
well as military vehicles and warships, will be similarly 
successful . 
  Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk referred to the fine 
cooperation 
traditions, especially from the interwar period. 
  [Begin Kolodziejczyk recording] Now we are going back to 
renewing these traditions. This refers also, or perhaps above 
all, to cooperation in the arms-manufacturing industry. Both 
sides are interested in this cooperation--Sweden and Poland 
equally. Our industry needs an injection of new technologies. 
It will thus be able to make use of its far-from-negligible 
intellectual and production potential. Sweden is agreeing to 
partnerlike cooperation--that is, not to the selling and buying 
of consumables but to investing their technologies in our 
industries. I hope the cooperation is going to be mutually 
beneficial. The first experiences, involving such well-known 
companies as Bofors and Ericsson, are behind us. These 
experiences were positive. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Minister Andres Bjorck emphasized that Poland 
was 
the first postcommunist country with which Sweden has signed an 
agreement on cooperation in the military field. 
  [Begin Bjorck recording, English with superimposed 
translation into Polish] Poland is the first country of the 
former Warsaw Treaty, and we had no doubts that that is how it 
was going to be--first, because your country is leading in 
making democratic changes in this part of the region, and, 
second, both our countries, which are neighbors across the 
Baltic, are interested in maintaining peace and stability in the 
region. Sweden believes peace will not come by itself. It is 
raising its spending for defense purposes that could serve our 
cooperation. It is also important to give content to 
Partnership for Peace, in which our countries are participating. 
[end recording] 
  [Announcer] Andres Bjorck also expressed the hope that 
Russia 
would join Partnership for Peace and would not be guided by 
particular interests. 
  The Swedish minister was received by President Lech Walesa 
and Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55501 </DOCNO>
