<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baudys Notes Russian `Volcano,' Instability </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baudys Notes Russian `Volcano,' Instability </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605122894 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1000 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] An international seminar on security issues in 
Central and East Europe began in Prague today. Miroslav 
Konvalina has been following its proceedings in the Atrium Hotel: 
  [Konvalina] The opening speeches and early discussions 
indicate that deputies from East and West European countries, 
politicians, journalists, and other participants in the seminar 
are eager to get to know not only our positions on NATO and 
other European institutions, but also the changing policy of 
Russia, its self-confident actions on foreign and security 
issues and, in this context, ways of facing a possible change of 
Russian policy. 
  In the opening address at the seminar, Defense Minister 
Antonin Baudys analyzed security risks in present-day Europe. 
He said Russia is a volcano, whose lava of instability could 
spill far beyond the borders. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Pavel Bratinka noted that Russia has 
also received an offer to join the Partnership for Peace program 
and that, in the West, there is no country aspiring to threaten 
Russia. That is why our efforts aimed at gaining NATO 
membership are not motivated primarily by our fear of Russia, 
but by our endeavor to embody the values we have in common with 
West Europe in joint institutions. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

