<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Speaker Comments on Future Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assembly Speaker Comments on Future Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605193694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1700 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Assembly Speaker Miro Lazovic 
said today that the Assembly of the Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Assembly of the Bosnian-Croat 
federation were going to share their work. I expect the 
Assembly of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina to meet. 
According to the Constitution, it should take up the duties of 
the federation's assembly with the proviso that at that session, 
duties will be divided into two categories -- tasks covered by 
the republic's Assembly and those relating to the future 
federation. 
  I believe that -- if political agreement is reached -- it 
will be possible to appoint top-level officials of the future 
federation. Some issues relating to the Assembly of the Republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina will also be examined, Lazovic said at a 
news conference in Zagreb. The news conference was organized by 
a delegation of the Serb Civic Council of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Miro Lazovic is its member. He stressed that in the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina parliament there are deputies who had been 
elected in the 1990 elections. He said he expected Croatian 
Democratic Community [HDZ] deputies to come and take part in the 
assembly's work -- in their capacity as representatives of a 
party that contested the 1990 elections rather than as 
representatives of Herceg-Bosna. 
  Lazovic pointed out that the federal concept outlined in the 
Washington agreement should be extended to the whole of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. We believe that this is a concept that 
suits the Bosnian Serbs, too, as they are the second largest 
population group in Bosnia-Herzegovina. If this concept is not 
accepted, a huge number of the Serbs who stay to live in the 
territory of the Croat-Bosnian federation will fall into the 
category of other peoples, although they will account for almost 
the same percentage as the Croats. 

</TEXT>

