<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Drastic Drop' in Trade Union Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Drastic Drop' in Trade Union Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605153194 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1200 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Over the past four years, there has been a drastic 
drop in trade union membership in the Czech Republic. Of the 
initial 92 percent, membership has dropped to the present 36 
percent. Only 22 percent of the work force employed in private 
companies are trade union members, said Jaroslav Strait, 
chairman of the Trade Unions Association of Bohemia, Moravia, 
and Silesia. He said that the current trend in the development 
of the trade union movement is worrying. What is disappearing 
is not only trade unions but also ordinary human solidarity, 
Strait said, adding that the pressure the state exerts on the 
social and economic rights of the people has strongly 
intensified and that ever tougher standards are asked for. 
  Strait said that all of this is happening with the help of 
the Czech-Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions. He branded this 
organization as a government-run trade union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

