<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   HZDS Tops Poll on Current Voting Intentions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    HZDS Tops Poll on Current Voting Intentions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605201594 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Summary] According to an opinion poll carried out by 
Slovak Radio in May to find out current voting intentions, and 
based on the answers from 1,065 respondents, the Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia [HZDS] polled 21.1 percent, the Party of the 
Democratic Left [SDL] polled 8.7 percent, and the Christian 
Democratic Movement [KDH] polled 7.9 percent of votes. The 
other parties failed to reach 5 percent of votes and would not 
therefore be represented in parliament. 
  The respondents also answered the question about how would 
they vote if parties and movements were grouped in coalitions. 
The coalition of national oriented parties--the HZDS, the 
Slovak National Party, and the Christian Social Union--would win 
1999 percent of votes. The coalition of left-wing parties--the 
SDL, the Social Democratic Party, the Green Party, and the 
Farmers' Movement--would win 15.1 percent of votes. And the 
coalition of right-wing and liberal parties--the KDH, the 
Democratic Party, the National Democratic Party, the Democratic 
Union, and the Party of Entrepreneurs and Small 
Businessmen--would win 13 percent of votes. The coalition of 
Hungarian parties received the support of 7.5 percent of 
respondents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

